pullRequest.body:
Transfer the existence theorem of local flows on vector spaces to manifolds. The precise statement is:
> If a vector field `v` on a manifold `M` is continuously differentiable at an interior point `x‚ÇÄ`, then for a given `t‚ÇÄ` there exists a neighbourhood `u` of `x‚ÇÄ`, a positive `Œµ`, and `Œ≥ : M ‚Üí ‚Ñù ‚Üí M` such that `Œ≥ x` is an integral curve of `v` on `(t‚ÇÄ - Œµ, t‚ÇÄ + Œµ)` for all `x ‚àà u`.

This is powerful because all curves `Œ≥ x` (each with initial condition `x ‚àà u`) share the same existence time interval `(t‚ÇÄ - Œµ, t‚ÇÄ + Œµ)`, rather than each curve having its own `Œµ`. This will allow us to show that $C^1$ vector fields on compact manifolds always have global integral curves / global flows.

Any suggestions to shorten the proof or split out useful lemmas are welcome!

- [ ] depends on: #20733

---
